Another Trojan horse strategy - well played
Good point. I’m a radonc in Canada so consider me the least qualified person to comment.
This! Once you are on site doing double reads you have traction and are sticky. Allows time to build trust and convert slowly to primary read. Medicine does not do paradigm shifts overnight.
I think my point is the companies that do double reading right will have the best chance at the decision making implementation. Could be wrong though!

Yes the “Med malpractice will save us” argument has been used (USA! USA!). Don’t bet on it. Massive scale MD rad labor cost saving models will factor Med mal insurance premiums. And as for govt healthcare systems... https://www. radiologybusiness.com/topics/healthc are-economics-policy/uks-nhs-radiology-services-under-review-after-20000-x-rays-go …

Not disagreeing. Just saying we shouldn't expect companies to shy away from real decision making systems. They will chase the market, and the market will chase cost savings. Double reading isn't a billion dollar idea.
We had a slight change of topic. @joshgiambi was asking about AI implementation more generally I think.
But failure will eventually happen and in autonomous scenario the shitstorm will be much nastier.

Biopsies are an endpoint in breast cancer research. Significant negative patient impact. Other than that, I agree. Honestly, the evidence for breast screening at all is borderline enough that we still argue about it, let alone whether double reading actually makes a difference.
There is a difference though - double reporting is performed independently. So the human-machine interaction will be at arbitration.
Autonomous driving is the perfect counter-example. 3 fatalities in human augmented driving, none in completely autonomous driving. Waymo is skipping level 3 driving for a reason.

Fewer biopsies or detecting more cancer is not the same as demonstrating better outcomes (survival, quality of life etc). But this really comes down to a debate about mammography screening in general.
